ROUTE(8)                       System Manager's Manual                    ROUTE(8)

NAME
       route - show / manipulate the IP routing table

SYNOPSIS
       route [-nNvee] [-FC] [family]
       route [-v] [-FC] add [-net|-host] target [netmask Nm] [gw Gw]
             [metric N] [mss M] [window W] [irtt I] [reject] [mod]
             [dyn] [reinstate] [[dev] If]
       route [-v] [-FC] del [-net|-host] target [gw Gw] [netmask Nm]
             [metric M] [[dev] If]
       route [-V|--version] [-h|--help]

DESCRIPTION
       Route manipulates the kernel's IP routing tables. Its primary
       use is to set up static routes to specific hosts or networks
       via an interface after it has been configured with the
       ifconfig(8) program.

       When the add or del options are used, route modifies the routing
       tables. Without these options, route displays the current
       contents of the routing tables.

OPTIONS
       -A family
              Use the specified address family (e.g. use -A inet6 for
              IPv6 routes). Only "inet" is supported on LikeOS.

       -F     Operate on the kernel FIB (Forwarding Information Base)
              routing tables. This is the default.

       -C     Operate on the kernel's routing cache. Not specially
              handled on LikeOS.

       -v     Select verbose operation.

       -n     Show numerical addresses instead of trying to determine
              symbolic host names. This is useful if you are trying
              to determine why the route to your nameserver has vanished.

       -e     Use netstat(8)-format for displaying the routing table.
              -ee will generate a very long line with all parameters
              from the routing table.

       -N     Try to resolve hardware names.

       -4     Display IPv4 routes (default).

       -6     Display IPv6 routes (not supported).

       -V, --version
              Display the version of route and exit.

       -h, --help
              Display help text and exit.

   ROUTE MODIFICATION
       del    Delete a route.

       add    Add a new route.

       target The destination network or host. You can provide IP
              addresses in dotted decimal or host/network names.

       -net   The target is a network.

       -host  The target is a host.

       netmask NM
              When adding a network route, the netmask to be used.

       gw GW  Route packets via a gateway.
              NOTE: The specified gateway must be reachable first. This
              usually means that you have to set up a static route to
              the gateway beforehand.

       metric M
              Set the metric field in the routing table (used by
              routing daemons) to M.

       mss M  Set the TCP Maximum Segment Size (MSS) for connections
              over this route to M bytes.

       window W
              Set the TCP window size for connections over this route
              to W bytes.

       irtt I Set the initial round trip time (irtt) for TCP
              connections over this route to I milliseconds.

       reject Install a blocking route, which will force a route
              lookup to fail. This is used to mask out networks
              before using the default route.

       mod, dyn, reinstate
              Install a modified, dynamic, or reinstated route.

       dev If Force the route to be associated with the specified
              device. If dev If is the last option on the command
              line, the word dev may be omitted.

EXAMPLES
       route
              Display the routing table.

       route -n
              Display the routing table numerically.

       route add default gw 192.168.1.1
              Add a default gateway.

       route add -net 10.0.0.0 netmask 255.0.0.0 gw 192.168.1.1
              Add a route to the 10.0.0.0/8 network.

       route add -host 192.168.1.100 dev eth0
              Add a host route via eth0.

       route del default
              Delete the default route.

       route del -net 10.0.0.0 netmask 255.0.0.0
              Delete the route to 10.0.0.0/8.

       route add -net 172.16.0.0 netmask 255.240.0.0 reject
              Add a reject route.

SEE ALSO
       ifconfig(8), netstat(8), arp(8)

